  "riddle": "1. Seek the Wikipedia article covering the boys' shot-put contest held at the inaugural 2010 Summer Youth Olympics; from that event summary, how many competitors are recorded as having taken part?\n\n2. If you take the numeral you just uncovered and flip its digits end-for-end, what new number emerges from that reversal?\n\n3. There exists a biography of the young gold medallist from that competition; on that page, record his best throw using the 5 kg shot, expressed in metres.\n\n4. If you then consult the nation-level report for the athlete's homeland at the same 2010 Games, answer this plainly: how many people live in that country (current population)?\n\n5. The article focused on that country's participation conceals a little arithmetic: replace the population number with the count of its positive integer divisors — how many divisors does that figure have?\n\n6. In the entry detailing Germany's team at those Youth Olympics you will find comparative links; for this clue, once again determine the population of the medallist's nation (as a check you should get the same total you found before).\n\n7. The page for Poland's delegation likewise points outward; here too, fetch how many inhabitants the athlete's island nation counts.\n\n8. One aside in the trail: for the central region of New York State, what is the elevation above mean sea level at its geographic heart (answer in metres)?\n\n9. Finally, compute the digital root of the sum (clue 1 + clue 3 + clue 5) and give that single digit (0–9) as your final answer.",
